    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"459699\">@Joël Riou</span>! Just for my understanding (as I don't come from a set-theoretic background) - are these mathematically the same sort of issues that occur with say the use of universes in SGA4?</p>",
        "id": 535063062,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryan Wang",
        "timestamp": 1755585290
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There is <em>no issue</em> with the use of the universes for the definition of étale cohomology in SGA 4. The key-observation are SGA 4 VII 1.7 and 3.1 (which are essentially what my PR <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/19462\">#19462</a> intends to formalize).</p>",
        "id": 535085679,
        "sender_full_name": "Joël Riou",
        "timestamp": 1755594556
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah I don't mean 'issue' as in 'problem', I mean 'something to be done' (like github issues <span aria-label=\"stuck out tongue closed eyes\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f61d\" role=\"img\" title=\"stuck out tongue closed eyes\">:stuck_out_tongue_closed_eyes:</span>)</p>",
        "id": 535087483,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryan Wang",
        "timestamp": 1755595279
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yep something like SGA 4 VII 1.7 is what I was looking for!</p>",
        "id": 535087565,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryan Wang",
        "timestamp": 1755595305
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What about sheaf cohomology in the usual sense - do we have enough to formulate that also? I found the discussion here <a class=\"stream-topic\" data-stream-id=\"335062\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/335062-homology/topic/Roadmap.20for.20sheaf.20cohomology/with/528343517\">#homology &gt; Roadmap for sheaf cohomology</a> but the discussion there seems to be centered around Cech cohomology.</p>",
        "id": 535218347,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryan Wang",
        "timestamp": 1755648411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By \"usual sense\", you mean sheaf cohomology on a topological space? Then yes, we have it without any universe bumps:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CategoryTheory</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">universe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">TopCat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">})</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Sheaf</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Opens</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">grothendieckTopology</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ab</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">})</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">instance</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsGrothendieckAbelian</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ab</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">of_equivalence</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">((</span><span class=\"n\">ModuleCat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">restrictScalarsEquivalenceOfRingEquiv</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">ULift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">ringEquiv</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">symm</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">forget₂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ModuleCat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℤ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ab</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">})</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">asEquivalence</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">instance</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">HasExt</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Sheaf</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Opens</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">grothendieckTopology</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ab</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">})</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">CategoryTheory</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">hasExt_of_enoughInjectives</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">H</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>But this is only the definition, apart from the general machinery, we have no results about it (yet). Much more theory about quasi-coherent sheafs is needed, before we can say anything interesting about Zariski cohomology.</p>",
        "id": 535265804,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1755679248
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's great, thanks! Maybe it is a good first step to develop enough theory to show vanishing of the cohomology of quasi-coherent sheaves on (noetherian) affine schemes. Though I am not sure how high that is in terms of usefulness-to-effort-needed ratio.</p>",
        "id": 535331590,
        "sender_full_name": "Bryan Wang",
        "timestamp": 1755701345
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>First step: define qc sheaf of modules :-) Definitely high usefulness-to-effort-needed ratio!</p>",
        "id": 535351061,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1755706998
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We have quasi coherent sheafs (<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=SheafOfModules.IsQuasicoherent#doc\">docs#SheafOfModules.IsQuasicoherent</a>). The current road blocker is showing that <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ModuleCat.tilde#doc\">docs#ModuleCat.tilde</a> is quasi-coherent. For this someone has to show that:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>ModuleCat.tilde</code> is functorial.</li>\n<li>This functor is exact.</li>\n<li>Easy: deduce <code>ModuleCat.tilde</code> is quasi-coherent.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For this we should show a bunch of properties of <code>ModuleCat.tilde</code> which we already have for the structure sheaf. The standard textbook trick to do this is to say: The construction of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>M</mi><mo>~</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\tilde M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9202em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9202em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.6023em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.1667em;\"><span class=\"mord\">~</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is the same as the one for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">O</mi><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{O}_{\\mathrm{Spec} R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9694em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0278em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">Spec</span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, so everything works the same way.<br>\nCurrently, Lean does not agree with this strategy because <code>LocalizedModule</code> and <code>Localization</code> are not def-eq. So <code>ModuleCat.tilde</code> is a re-implementation of the structure sheaf for modules, so we would have to duplicate all proofs.<br>\nHence, the <em>right</em> way to do this is to fix and merge <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/13156\">#13156</a> (by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"439483\">@Andrew Yang</span>) which unifies <code>LocalizedModule</code> and <code>Localization</code>.  Then, hopefully, we should be able to just replace <code>R</code> by <code>M</code> in the construction of the structure sheaf and everything should still work.</p>",
        "id": 535354370,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1755708126
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That said, given the state of <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/13156\">#13156</a>, if you are happy to develop functoriality and exactness of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ModuleCat.tilde#doc\">docs#ModuleCat.tilde</a>, feel free to go ahead. It will certainly be useful, even if it gets refactored later. But I have to warn you that working with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ModuleCat.tilde#doc\">docs#ModuleCat.tilde</a> is a bit rough right now, because there is very little API for it.</p>",
        "id": 535356470,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Merten",
        "timestamp": 1755709013
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So what's the deal with <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/13156\">#13156</a>, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"439483\">@Andrew Yang</span> ?</p>",
        "id": 535357865,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1755709593
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I redid it again in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/25662\">#25662</a> but it has also rotten again. I'm on holiday now but I can fix it if there are people willing to review it before it rots yet again.</p>",
        "id": 535405870,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1755733871
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd be very happy to develop <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=ModuleCat.tilde#doc\">docs#ModuleCat.tilde</a> further, but I agree that we should probably first \"fix\" <code>LocalizedModule</code>, or we might run into more problems down the road..?</p>",
